4. ALTERNATIVE (lighter-weight, no REST module) — @JSONWebService
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Skip section 2 entirely and annotate the local service method instead:

	@JSONWebService
	public InterestRate findByCustomerType_Product_Tenure(
			String customerType, String productCode, int tenureDays)
		throws PortalException { ... }

Call it from index.js with Liferay's built-in helper (handles the portal's
CSRF token and auth cookie for you):

	Liferay.Service(
		'/interestrate.interestrate/find-by-customer-type-product-tenure',
		{customerType: customerType, productCode: productCode, tenureDays: tenureDays},
		function(rate) { setOutput('interestRate', rate.interestRatePct + '%'); }
	);

Trade-off vs. section 2: less code to ship, but the payload/URL shape is tied
to the service's Java method signature (breaks silently if you rename/reorder
params), there's no OpenAPI contract for other consumers, and GET-style
caching doesn't apply since jsonws calls are POSTed. Fine for an internal,
single-fragment integration; REST Builder earns its keep once more than one
client needs these rates or the contract needs to be stable long-term.

